06014nam a22010095i 9783110638950DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106389507 a10.1515/97831106389502doi  a(DE-B1597)530604  a(OCoLC)1163878880  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aTP248.23b.J63 2020 7aREL0500002bisacsh04a303.4832231 aJobin, Guy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpirituality in the Biomedical World :bMoving between Order and “Subversion” /cGuy Jobin. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (X, 174 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Spiritual Care ,x2511-8838 ;v500tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Tables -- t1. Introduction -- tPart I. Order, or the sapientialization of the spiritual experience -- t2. About wisdom -- t3. A new biomedical order? -- t4. Sapientialization of the spiritual question -- t5. Pragmatic approaches to sapientialization -- t6. Challenges to sapientialization -- tPart II. The “subversive” nature of spirituality in healthcare -- t7. Questions relating to spiritual anthropology -- t8. The spiritual experience as a response to an event -- t9. Spiritual life and traditions during illness -- t10. Conclusion -- tCredits -- tBibliography -- tIndex nominum -- tIndex rerum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe need to take the spiritual experience during illness into account is part of a broader trend in Western societies—a fascination with the practical uses of spirituality and its contribution to individual wellbeing, whether through a religious or a humanist tradition. This understanding of spirituality differs from traditional views embedded in religious traditions. This book takes a critical point of view at the biomedical representation of the function of spirituality in care. Medicine reorders notions such as life, death, health, sickness, and spirituality. This process is called here “sapientialization”, i.e. the spiritual experience is expressed and understood under the auspices of and in terms of wisdom. This view tends to identify spirituality and ethics. I propose an alternate understanding of spirituality, grounded on its subversive power. Inspired by the work of the theologian John D. Caputo, it is critical of some problems that are associated with the sapientialization of spirituality in biomedicine, such as the medicalization of spiritual experiences or the instrumentalization of spirituality. It provides an understanding of spirituality that honours both the medical interest in it and its capacity to resist to instrumentalization.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aBiotechnologyxReligious aspects. 0aMedical carexReligious aspects. 0aMedicinexReligious aspects. 0aReligion and science. 0aSpiritual care (Medical care). 0aSpirituality. 7aRELIGION / Christian Ministry / Counseling & Recovery.2bisacsh  aCritical Studies.  aSpiritual Care.  aSpirituality in Healthcare.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruy